# MKPE CODEOWNERS
#
# Rules in this file map paths to required reviewers. GitHub enforces them
# via branch protection on `main` (configured in repo settings, not here).
#
# As of Phase 1 MKPE has a single maintainer. CODEOWNERS still serves as
# documentation of which paths are security-sensitive so that any future
# contributor or automated review knows where the bar is highest.
#
# Update policy:
#   - Adding a reviewer to a path: routine PR, normal review.
#   - Removing a reviewer from a security-sensitive path: requires the
#     remaining owner of that path AND the security@vyrevault.studio
#     contact to approve.
#   - Adding new paths: include rationale in the commit message.

# ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Default: every change requires the maintainer's review.
# ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
* @RedWoodOG

# ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# CRITICAL -- cryptographic primitives. Changes here invalidate every existing
# attestation if done wrong. Require deep review even for trivial-looking diffs.
# ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
/core/src/crypto.rs        @RedWoodOG
/core/src/manifest.rs      @RedWoodOG
/core/src/proof.rs         @RedWoodOG
/core/src/bundle.rs        @RedWoodOG
/core/src/audit.rs         @RedWoodOG

# ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Supply-chain configuration. Loosening these is how silent compromise enters
# a codebase. PR templates should call out any change to these files.
# ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
/Cargo.toml                @RedWoodOG
/Cargo.lock                @RedWoodOG
/rust-toolchain.toml       @RedWoodOG
/deny.toml                 @RedWoodOG
/supply-chain/             @RedWoodOG

# ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# CI / build workflows. The workflow IS the SLSA trust anchor. A compromised
# workflow file means every signed artifact afterward is suspect.
# ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
/.github/workflows/        @RedWoodOG
/.github/CODEOWNERS        @RedWoodOG

# ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Provenance schemas and verifier surface. Format changes must keep backwards
# compatibility with the entire history of issued attestations.
# ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
/schemas/                  @RedWoodOG
/cli/src/verify*.rs        @RedWoodOG

# ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Security policy documents. Changes are governance acts, not code edits.
# ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
/SECURITY.md               @RedWoodOG
/docs/security/            @RedWoodOG
/docs/SLSA_PLAN.md         @RedWoodOG
